28:17.145 --> 28:18.646
right in front of
my very eyes.

28:18.646 --> 28:20.280
Ears.
Ears.

28:20.281 --> 28:21.782
'Scuse me.

28:23.234 --> 28:25.236
Well, obviously the cracked
crab did not work out.

28:25.236 --> 28:27.238
Just put that down, if you
don't want your hand slapped.

28:27.238 --> 28:28.239
I'm about to
have some.

28:28.239 --> 28:30.241
I just wanna pour off
the melted ice.

28:31.242 --> 28:32.743
You know, sometimes
you remind me

28:32.744 --> 28:34.245
of the Chinese
water torture.

28:34.245 --> 28:35.746
No, no, no.
I take that back.

28:35.747 --> 28:37.749
Sometimes you remind me
of the relentless

28:37.749 --> 28:39.083
Chinese water
torture.

28:39.084 --> 28:40.502
Bitch.

28:42.587 --> 28:43.588
Hey, I wonder where
Harold is.

28:43.588 --> 28:45.590
Yeah, where is
the frozen fruit?

28:45.590 --> 28:47.592
Emory refers to Harold as the frozen fruit

28:47.592 --> 28:50.094
because of his former profession
as an ice skater.

28:50.095 --> 28:53.598
She used to be the Vera Hruba
Ralston of the borscht circuit.

28:53.598 --> 28:55.099
Time for your
rhythm injection.

28:55.100 --> 28:58.103
Now, how did you guess I didn't
want to lie down, Bernard?

28:58.103 --> 28:59.604
You know, if your mother
could see you now,

28:59.604 --> 29:00.605
she'd have a stroke.

29:00.605 --> 29:01.606
You got a camera
on you?

29:01.606 --> 29:03.107
All right, Emily,
up here right now.

29:03.108 --> 29:04.109
Look
out.

29:04.109 --> 29:06.528
Look at those
twinkle toes. Heh.

29:08.113 --> 29:09.697
Oh, my God, it's Lilly Law.

29:09.697 --> 29:10.698
Everyone
three feet apart.

29:10.698 --> 29:12.449
Quiet. Quiet!
It may be Harold.

29:14.035 --> 29:16.420
No, it's the delivery boy
from the bakery.

29:16.421 --> 29:18.423
Ask him if he's got
any hot-crossed buns.

29:20.291 --> 29:22.042
Come on, Emory.
Knock it off, will you?

29:22.043 --> 29:23.627
You can take her
anywhere but out.

29:23.628 --> 29:26.263
You remind me of
an old maid schoolteacher.

29:26.264 --> 29:28.516
You remind me of a chicken wing.

29:28.516 --> 29:30.100
I'm sure you meant that
as a compliment.

29:31.386 --> 29:32.387
Um, thank you.
Good night.

29:38.393 --> 29:40.027
Hey, Bernard? Do you
remember that dance

29:40.028 --> 29:42.030
we used to do
at Fire Island?

29:42.030 --> 29:45.033
Man, that was in so far back,
I think I've forgotten it.

29:45.033 --> 29:46.534
I remember it.

29:48.036 --> 29:49.537
One, two.
One, two.

29:49.537 --> 29:50.538
Oh, Christ.

29:50.538 --> 29:52.540
Single, single.
Dance.

29:52.540 --> 29:54.041
All right.
Whoo!

29:54.042 --> 29:56.744
Wait a minute.
One, two, three, four.

29:56.744 --> 29:58.746
It's the geriatrics
Rockettes.

30:00.415 --> 30:02.417
Get 'em up there,
huh, babe. Whoo!

30:02.417 --> 30:03.918
One, two.
Who dreamed this up?

30:03.918 --> 30:05.419
Emory.

30:05.420 --> 30:08.506
It's the sensational
Menstruations.

30:10.725 --> 30:12.259
Come on, Donald.
Get in here.

30:12.260 --> 30:13.010
Ah!

30:13.011 --> 30:14.679
Get your hand
off my ass.

30:14.679 --> 30:15.730
Very funny.

30:20.185 --> 30:21.102
Whoa!

30:22.437 --> 30:23.488
Look, baby.

30:43.258 --> 30:44.292
Is Mike in?

30:49.797 --> 30:51.298
<i>♪ Like a heat wave ♪</i>

30:51.299 --> 30:52.216
<i>♪ Burning in my heart ♪</i>

30:52.217 --> 30:54.352
<i>♪ Like a heat wave ♪</i>

30:54.352 --> 30:55.436
Michael!

30:59.440 --> 31:01.525
Michael!
Michael.

31:05.563 --> 31:06.564
<i>♪ Heat wave ♪</i>

31:06.564 --> 31:08.732
Um-- I, uh--

31:08.733 --> 31:11.035
I thought you weren't coming.
I'm sorry.

31:11.035 --> 31:12.619
Um. We were-- We were
just acting silly.

31:12.620 --> 31:13.904
Actually, when
I called,

31:13.905 --> 31:15.990
I-- I was in a phone booth
just around the corner.

31:15.990 --> 31:17.074
My dinner party's
not far from here.

31:17.075 --> 31:19.410
Um, Emory was just showing us--
When I walked past,

31:19.410 --> 31:20.577
the downstairs door
was open,

31:20.578 --> 31:22.162
so I just--
Oh, excuse me. This is Emory.

31:23.882 --> 31:25.250
Hello.

31:26.334 --> 31:29.337
Everybody, this is
Alan McCarthy.

31:29.337 --> 31:31.922
Alan, um--
Counterclockwise.

31:31.923 --> 31:34.425
Larry and Emory,
and Bernard...

31:34.425 --> 31:36.477
How are you?
...Donald and Hank.

31:36.477 --> 31:38.262
Hello, it's nice to meet you.
It's nice to meet you.

31:39.564 --> 31:41.315
Uh, well, can I get you
a drink?

31:41.316 --> 31:43.318
Uh, Scotch, please.

31:43.318 --> 31:44.402
Fine.
Uh-- I'll get it.

31:44.402 --> 31:46.404
Oh. Thank you,
Donald.

31:46.404 --> 31:48.406
Well, I guess I'm the only
beer drinker here tonight.

31:52.193 --> 31:54.912
Whose, uh--
Whose birthday is it?

31:54.913 --> 31:56.781
Oh, it's--
Harold's.

31:58.082 --> 31:59.416
Harold.

31:59.417 --> 32:02.503
He's not here yet.
She's never been on time--

32:02.503 --> 32:05.789
<i>He's</i> never been on time
in <i>his</i> life.

32:05.790 --> 32:07.291
Uh, H-Hank.
Alan is from Washington.

32:07.292 --> 32:09.294
Washington.
We went to college together.

32:09.294 --> 32:10.378
Georgetown.

32:10.378 --> 32:12.213
Isn't that
fascinating?

32:12.213 --> 32:13.797
Here. If that's too strong,

32:13.798 --> 32:14.799
I'll put some
water in it.

32:17.802 --> 32:19.270
No. It's fine, thanks.
Fine.

32:19.270 --> 32:21.555
Well, Alan, are you in the government then--?

32:21.556 --> 32:22.640
No, I'm a lawyer.
What do you do?

32:22.640 --> 32:24.141
Oh, I teach
school.

32:24.142 --> 32:26.144
Oh, I would've taken you for
an athlete of some sort.

32:26.144 --> 32:28.146
You look like you might
play sports of some sort.

32:28.146 --> 32:29.647
Well, I'm
no professional.

32:29.647 --> 32:31.649
I was on the basketball team in
college, and I do play tennis.

32:31.649 --> 32:33.651
Well, I play tennis too.
It's a great game.

32:33.651 --> 32:34.652
Yeah, that's great.

32:35.453 --> 32:37.872
Uh, yeah, it's a great game.

32:39.741 --> 32:41.743
What, uh... W-- What do
you teach?

32:41.743 --> 32:42.744
Math.
Math?

32:42.744 --> 32:44.579
Yeah.
Math, well...

32:44.579 --> 32:47.582
Makes you wanna rush out and buy
a slide rule, doesn't it?

32:47.582 --> 32:50.418
Uh, excuse me, Alan,
I'll be right back.

32:50.418 --> 32:52.503
Come on, Emory. I'm gonna need
some help in the kitchen.

32:52.503 --> 32:53.720
You're elected.

32:53.721 --> 32:56.306
I'm always elected.
You're a natural-born domestic.

32:56.307 --> 32:57.808
Said the African
queen.

32:57.809 --> 33:00.311
You come on too. You can fan me
while I make the salad dressing.

33:00.311 --> 33:02.813
Right this way,
Emory. Come on.

33:10.405 --> 33:11.906
Oh, hey,
look, uh...

33:11.906 --> 33:13.908
why don't we all
sit down over here?

33:13.908 --> 33:14.909
Sure.

33:24.919 --> 33:27.922
I, uh... I really feel terrible
about barging in

33:27.922 --> 33:29.423
on you fellows
this way.

33:34.128 --> 33:35.929
Well, that's perfectly
all right, Alan.

33:36.931 --> 33:38.265
Hi.
Hi.

33:42.970 --> 33:43.971
Hey, you're married?

33:45.973 --> 33:47.975
What?
I see you're married.

33:47.975 --> 33:49.526
Oh. Yes.

33:49.527 --> 33:51.612
Yes, Hank's married.

33:51.612 --> 33:53.113
Donald.

33:53.114 --> 33:54.115
Come up with some ice.

33:55.616 --> 33:56.483
Excuse me.

34:04.459 --> 34:05.460
Oh!

34:12.132 --> 34:14.502
Do you, uh--
Do you have any kids?

34:15.386 --> 34:18.054
Yes. Yes, I have two.

34:18.056 --> 34:20.757
I have a boy, nine,
and a girl, seven.

34:20.757 --> 34:22.309
They're great kids too.

34:22.310 --> 34:23.393
You should see my boy
play tennis.

34:23.393 --> 34:24.928
He really puts
his dad to shame.

34:24.929 --> 34:26.513
I've got two kids too.
Both girls.

34:26.514 --> 34:28.315
Hey, that's great.
How are the girls, Alan?

34:28.315 --> 34:30.400
Oh, they're just sensational.
They're...

34:30.400 --> 34:32.018
really something, those kids.
God, I'm--

34:32.018 --> 34:33.603
I'm nuts
about them.

34:36.074 --> 34:38.076
Well, Alan, um, how long have
you been married, then?

34:38.076 --> 34:39.527
Nine years.
Mm-hm.

34:39.527 --> 34:40.911
Can you believe it, Mickey?
No.

34:40.911 --> 34:43.030
Mickey used to go with my wife
when we were all in school.

34:43.030 --> 34:44.197
Can you believe that?

34:51.539 --> 34:53.541
Do you, uh...

34:53.541 --> 34:55.509
Do you live
in the city?

34:55.510 --> 34:57.211
Uh, yes, we do.

34:57.211 --> 35:00.297
I'm in the process
of getting a divorce. Uh...

35:00.298 --> 35:01.882
Larry and I are roommates
for the moment.

35:01.883 --> 35:02.884
Yes.

35:04.385 --> 35:06.603
I'm sorry, I-I--
I didn't mean to--

35:06.604 --> 35:08.188
No, no, it's perfectly
all right. I understand.

35:23.621 --> 35:25.489
Oh, I'm sorry.
Here. Let--

35:28.493 --> 35:31.496
Oh. Can I
help you, Alan?

35:31.496 --> 35:33.998
I can't seem to find
the Scotch. Uh...

35:33.998 --> 35:36.000
Well, you've got it
in your hand.

35:36.000 --> 35:38.469
Oh, where the hell
could Harold be?

35:38.469 --> 35:39.553
He's always
late.

35:39.554 --> 35:41.055
But why does it take Harold
hours to get ready

35:41.055 --> 35:42.556
before he can go out?

35:42.557 --> 35:45.009
Because she's a sick lady,
that's why.

35:46.093 --> 35:47.644
Alan, we can go
to my bedroom and talk.

35:47.645 --> 35:49.146
I'm just gonna
finish this and go.

35:49.147 --> 35:50.648
Come on, bring
your drink.

35:53.651 --> 35:54.652
I've finished it.

35:54.652 --> 35:55.653
Oh.

36:06.164 --> 36:07.665
Excuse us. We'll be down
in just a minute.

36:07.665 --> 36:08.666
Sure. Sure.

36:08.666 --> 36:10.501
Oh, um...he'll still
be here.

36:11.919 --> 36:12.920
This way, Alan.

36:22.129 --> 36:24.131
Now, just what was that
supposed to mean?

36:25.633 --> 36:28.135
What was what
supposed to mean?

36:28.135 --> 36:30.137
You know, that little--
Hey, you want another beer?

36:30.137 --> 36:32.189
Hey. You're jealous,
aren't you?

36:34.725 --> 36:35.692
No.

36:38.112 --> 36:40.948
I'm Larry.
You're jealous.

36:42.783 --> 36:45.902
The last time I saw you,
you were on your way to...

36:45.903 --> 36:48.906
California, or--
Or was it Europe?

36:48.906 --> 36:50.407
Hollywood.

36:50.408 --> 36:52.410
Which is not in Europe, and
which has nothing whatsoever

36:52.410 --> 36:53.911
to do with
California.

36:53.911 --> 36:56.914
Well, I've-- I've never
been there myself,

36:56.914 --> 36:58.916
but I would imagine
it must be awful.

36:58.916 --> 37:00.417
Everyone must be...

37:00.418 --> 37:01.635
terribly cheap.

37:02.720 --> 37:04.505
No. Not everyone.

37:04.505 --> 37:06.840
Alan...

37:06.841 --> 37:08.342
I'd like to try to
explain about tonight.

37:08.342 --> 37:09.843
What's to explain?

37:09.844 --> 37:14.932
Sometimes you can't invite
everyone to every party,

37:14.932 --> 37:16.767
and some people
take it personally.

37:16.767 --> 37:20.020
But I-- I'm not
one of them. I...

37:20.021 --> 37:21.989
should apologize
for inviting myself.

37:21.989 --> 37:23.573
Well, that's not
exactly what I meant.

37:23.574 --> 37:25.075
Your friends,
uh...

37:25.076 --> 37:28.829
Your friends all seem like
very nice guys.

37:28.829 --> 37:29.913
That, uh...

37:29.914 --> 37:32.783
That Hank, he's really
a very attractive fellow.

37:33.668 --> 37:34.535
Yes, he is.

37:37.922 --> 37:39.924
We've got a lot in common.

37:41.425 --> 37:42.926
What's his roommate's name?

37:43.928 --> 37:45.429
Larry.

37:45.429 --> 37:46.463
And what does he do?

37:46.464 --> 37:47.965
He's a fashion photographer.

37:49.383 --> 37:50.884
And I like Donald too.

37:50.885 --> 37:55.389
The only one I didn't seem to
care too much for is...

37:55.389 --> 37:58.892
wh-wh-what's
his name? Uh...Emory?

38:00.278 --> 38:02.780
Yes. Emory.

38:04.231 --> 38:05.782
Well, I just can't
stand that kind of talk.

38:05.783 --> 38:07.785
It just
grates on me.

38:09.787 --> 38:12.790
Uh, what kind of talk, Alan?

38:12.790 --> 38:16.293
You know what
I mean. His...

38:16.294 --> 38:17.795
His brand of humor,
I suppose.

38:17.795 --> 38:20.164
Well, he can be
quite funny sometimes.

38:20.164 --> 38:22.666
I suppose so, if you find
that sort of thing amusing.

38:22.667 --> 38:25.169
It's just that he seems like
such a goddamn little pansy.

38:33.477 --> 38:35.979
I'm-- I'm s--
I'm sorry I said that. I--

38:38.983 --> 38:40.985
I didn't mean to say that.
That's such an awful thing

38:40.985 --> 38:41.986
to say about anyone.

38:41.986 --> 38:43.604
You know what
I mean, Michael.

38:43.604 --> 38:45.155
You must admit,
he is effeminate.

38:47.074 --> 38:48.075
Yes, he is a bit.

38:48.075 --> 38:49.276
A bit?

38:50.861 --> 38:53.864
Why-- Why he's like a--

38:53.864 --> 38:55.866
He's like
a butterfly in heat.

38:59.003 --> 39:01.088
I mean, it's-- It's no wonder
that he was trying

39:01.088 --> 39:02.089
to teach you all to dance.

39:02.089 --> 39:04.591
He probably wanted to
dance with you.

39:09.797 --> 39:12.299
Oh, come on, man. You--

39:12.299 --> 39:15.218
You know me.
You know how I feel.

39:15.219 --> 39:16.637
Your...

39:16.637 --> 39:19.139
Your private life
is your own affair.

39:20.107 --> 39:22.642
No, I don't know
that about you.

39:24.645 --> 39:26.146
Well, I--

39:26.147 --> 39:30.151
I couldn't care less
about what people do, as...

39:30.151 --> 39:31.535
As long as they don't
do it in public,

39:31.535 --> 39:34.120
or try to force their ways
on the whole damned world.

39:36.123 --> 39:38.625
Alan, what were you
crying about on the telephone?

39:46.584 --> 39:47.635
All I--

39:50.638 --> 39:52.640
All I can say is,
please forgive me

39:52.640 --> 39:54.058
for making
such an ass of myself.

39:59.346 --> 40:00.347
You must have been upset,

40:00.347 --> 40:02.849
or you wouldn't have said
that you were.

40:02.850 --> 40:05.068
That you were upset
and that you wanted to see me.

40:05.069 --> 40:07.020
Had to see me,
and talk to me.

40:07.021 --> 40:08.238
Michael, please.

40:10.324 --> 40:12.159
Is something wrong
between you and Fran?

40:14.995 --> 40:16.413
Listen,
I've really got to go.

40:16.414 --> 40:17.364
Why are you in New York?

40:18.783 --> 40:21.285
I'm dreadfully late
for dinner, Michael.

40:21.285 --> 40:24.087
Whose dinner?
Where are you going?

40:29.176 --> 40:30.760
Oh, no!
Oh! Here.

40:30.761 --> 40:32.129
Come on.

40:32.129 --> 40:33.180
Here, I'll get the--

40:33.180 --> 40:35.048
Uh-oh. Denise Deluge.

40:35.049 --> 40:37.468
Oh, great.
Now it's stopped.

40:39.887 --> 40:41.471
Oh, Hank.

40:41.472 --> 40:43.056
Why don't you
come and join us?

40:45.559 --> 40:48.028
Well, that's an interesting
suggestion. Whose idea was that?

40:48.979 --> 40:50.981
Well, mine.

40:50.981 --> 40:52.782
He means
in the conversation.

40:55.453 --> 40:56.570
To your health.

40:56.570 --> 40:58.455
Up yours.

40:58.456 --> 40:59.824
Up my health?

41:01.125 --> 41:02.126
Where's the gent?

41:02.126 --> 41:03.627
In the gents' room.

41:05.129 --> 41:07.131
If you can hang on
for five more minutes,

41:07.131 --> 41:08.132
he's about to leave.

41:09.633 --> 41:11.134
Well, at last.

41:13.637 --> 41:16.973
♪ Happy birthday to you
Happy birthday to you ♪

41:16.974 --> 41:19.559
♪ Happy birthday, dear Harold
Happy birthday to you ♪

41:19.560 --> 41:20.844
Don't--

41:20.845 --> 41:23.230
Who the hell are you?
Well, uh--

41:23.230 --> 41:25.315
She's Harold's present
from me, and she's early.

41:25.316 --> 41:27.318
And that's not even Harold,
you idiot!

41:27.318 --> 41:29.353
Well, you said
whoever answered the door.

41:29.353 --> 41:30.854
But not until
midnight.

41:30.855 --> 41:33.073
He's supposed to be
a midnight cowboy.

41:34.158 --> 41:36.276
He is a midnight
cowboy.

41:36.277 --> 41:38.362
He looks right out of a
William Inge play, doesn't he?

41:38.362 --> 41:40.781
Not until midnight,
and you're supposed to sing

41:40.781 --> 41:42.783
to the right person,
for chrissakes. I told you,

41:42.783 --> 41:46.002
Harold has very, very tight,
tight black curly hair.

41:46.003 --> 41:47.754
This number's
practically bald.

41:47.755 --> 41:48.956
Thank you, and fuck you.

41:48.956 --> 41:50.457
Good thing I didn't
open the door.

41:50.457 --> 41:52.542
Not that tight
and not that black.

41:52.543 --> 41:54.545
Aw, I forgot.

41:54.545 --> 41:57.214
And besides, I-I want to get
to the bars by midnight.

41:57.214 --> 41:58.848
He's a class act,
all the way around.

41:58.849 --> 42:00.433
What do you mean,
"get to the bars"?

42:00.434 --> 42:03.220
Sweetie, I paid you for
the whole evening, remember?

42:03.220 --> 42:05.305
Oh, I hurt my back
doing my exercises,

42:05.306 --> 42:07.274
and I want to get
to bed early tonight.

42:07.274 --> 42:08.358
Are you ready
for this one?

42:08.359 --> 42:10.894
Well, that's too bad.
What happened?

42:10.895 --> 42:12.980
I, uh... Heh.

42:12.980 --> 42:14.982
I-I lost my grip
doing my chin-ups,

42:14.982 --> 42:16.984
and I fell on my heels
and twisted my back.

42:16.984 --> 42:19.369
You shouldn't wear heels
when you do chin-ups.

42:24.458 --> 42:25.959
I-I shouldn't do
chin-ups.

42:25.960 --> 42:27.461
I have a weak grip
to begin with.

42:27.461 --> 42:30.747
A weak grip. In my day it used
to be called a limp wrist.

42:30.748 --> 42:33.167
Who can remember
that far back?

42:33.167 --> 42:34.251
Who was it who always
used to say,

42:34.251 --> 42:36.753
"You show me Oscar Wilde
in a cowboy suit,

42:36.754 --> 42:39.256
and I'll show you
a gay caballero"?

42:39.256 --> 42:41.258
I don't know. Who was it
who always used to say that?

42:41.258 --> 42:42.676
I don't know. Somebody.

42:42.676 --> 42:44.561
What does your card say?

42:44.562 --> 42:46.263
Uh, Y-you read it.

42:50.985 --> 42:53.737
"Dear Harold, bang, bang, you're alive,

42:53.737 --> 42:55.739
"but roll over
and play dead.

42:55.739 --> 42:57.774
Happy birthday. Emory."

42:57.775 --> 42:59.159
Sheer poetry, Emmy.

42:59.159 --> 43:01.244
And in your
usual good taste.

43:01.245 --> 43:04.998
Yes. And so conservative to have
resisted a sign in Times Square.

43:04.999 --> 43:07.368
